AVIAN INFLUENZA (67): CANADA (BRITISH COLUMBIA), LPAI H7, MIGRATORY
BIRD
************************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 2 Nov 2011
Source: Abbotsford Times [edited]
http://www.abbotsfordtimes.com/news/story.html?id=5647821


The Canadian Food Inspection Agency [CFIA] has found a low
pathogenicity H7 avian influenza [AI] virus in wild birds in central
and western Canada. The virus was found in healthy mallards by
Canada's Inter-Agency Wild Bird Influenza Survey, an early warning
system designed to detect AI viruses in the wild that could be
transmitted to domestic poultry, during regular testing during the
fall migratory season.

Regions such as the Fraser Valley are on wild bird flyways, although
this virus was identified in healthy live mallards sampled in Manitoba
and Saskatchewan in the course of regular testing during the fall
migratory season.

Low pathogenicity influenza viruses commonly circulate in the wild
bird population with little or no impact on the health of domestic
birds or people. However, the H5 and H7 AI viruses have been known to
mutate from low pathogenicity to highly pathogenic forms once
introduced into domestic poultry, potentially causing high rates of
disease and mortality in birds.

In February 2004, an avian influenza infected commercial poultry
flocks in the Fraser Valley. The CFIA ordered the killing of close to
19 million birds, the majority of which were healthy, as a pre-emptive
strike to control the spread of illness. The federal government
provided compensation to some farmers, although it didn't cover the
estimated CAN 400 million [about USD 392.4 million] in losses to the
region.

Since then, growers' organizations adopted bio-security measures to
reduce the risk of disease entering the commercial farm buildings.

The CFIA reminds flock owners to practise biosecurity cleanliness to
protect their flocks. If farmers suspect their birds are sick, they
should contact a veterinarian, the provincial ministry of agriculture,
or a local CFIA office toll-free at 1-800-442-2342.

[Byline: Christina Toth]

